<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910301-0084</DOCNO><DOCID>910301-0084.</DOCID><HL>   Credit Lyonnais Trims   Its Hong Kong Staff</HL><DATE>03/01/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C22</SO><CO>   F.CLC</CO><IN>SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><LP>   HONG KONG -- In the latest sign of widening cuts in thelocal securities industry, Credit Lyonnais Securities (Asia)Ltd., a unit of Credit Lyonnais SA, said it laid off sevenemployees at its Hong Kong office.   The layoffs of three researchers, two sales people and twosupport staff followed the recent shutdown of Morgan StanleyAsia Ltd.'s institutional brokerage division in Hong Kong andthe closure of BT Brokerage (HK) Ltd., a unit of BankersTrust Corp.</LP><TEXT>   Gary Coull, managing director of Credit Lyonnais,described the company's cuts as &quot;part cost control, partrationalization.&quot; Before the layoffs, Credit Lyonnaisemployed 135 people in five offices throughout the region.The bulk of the firm's employees in the region work in theHong Kong office. Its other offices are in Malaysia,Singapore, Thailand and Indonesia.   Mr. Coull said the brokerage firm's regional thrust won'tchange. He also said the cuts in Hong Kong reflect no changein the status of the office; &quot;Hong Kong is still ourstrongest office,&quot; Mr. Coull said.   BT Brokerage closed its Hong Kong office on Feb. 7, layingoff 46 people. On Feb. 18, Morgan Stanley said it was cuttingeight positions and shutting its institutional brokeragedivision. It plans further reductions among the division'ssupport staff during the next six months.   Both firms, like many others in Hong Kong, suffered fromthe extended decline in regional equities.</TEXT></DOC>